{{EngvarB|date=April 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}} {{Infobox person | name = Khethi Ngwenya | image = | caption = | birth_name = Khethi Ngwenya | birth_place = [[Soweto]], South Africa | birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1991|3|25}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://themediaonline.co.za/2016/12/five-ways-to-market-to-youth-in-2017/|title=Five ways to market to youth in 2017 - The Media Online|website=themediaonline.co.za}}</ref> | nationality = South African | occupation = Founder and Managing Director of SchoolMedia<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/SchoolMediaZA/photos/pcb.1217904431586400/1217903751586468/?type=3|title=SchoolMedia.co.za|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref> Co-Founder and Chairman of ContiLube SA
}} '''Khethi Ngwenya''' (born 25 March 1991 in [[Soweto]]) is a [[South African]] entrepreneur and businessman. He is the founder and managing director of SchoolMedia<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.changemakers.com/globalgoals2015/entries/khethi-ngwenyas-new-entry|title=Khethi Ngwenya&amp;#039;s New Entry|website=Changemakers}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://iono.fm/e/315228|title=CASE STUDY – SCHOOL MEDIA|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/mfonobongnsehe/2017/01/30/30-most-promising-young-entrepreneurs-in-africa-2017-nominate-now/|title=30 Most Promising Young Entrepreneurs In Africa 2017- Nominate Now|first=Mfonobong|last=Nsehe|publisher=}}</ref> South Africa's largest Media and community upliftment company within Schools across South Africa. He is also the co-founder of Contilube-SA as well as the Acting Deputy Curator of the Johannesburg [[Global Shapers]] Forum.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=https://medo.site/khethi-ngwenya-schoolmedia/|title=Khethi Ngwenya: SchoolMedia|date=15 October 2014|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://uniqmagazinesa.co.za/sexual-harassment-education-should-begin-at-school-level/|title=Sexual Harassment Education Should Begin At School Level – Magazine SA|website=uniqmagazinesa.co.za}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.globalshapers.org/shapers/khethi-ngwenya|title=Khethi Ngwenya - Global Shapers Community<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.globalshapers.org/news/khethi-shape-africa-update|title=Updates|website=Global Shapers}}</ref>
==Early life== Khethi Ngwenya was born on 25 March 1991 in [[Soweto]] South of [[Johannesburg]] to Mapula and Jabu Ngwenya and spend most of his early years in Mofolo [[Soweto]] and in [[Witbank]]. At a young age he started selling hair products in his aunt’s salon to make extra money during school holidays. At 12 he decided to open his own stall selling firecrackers to the local community. At a later stage he moved with his family to [[Alberton, Gauteng|Alberton]] and at 16 joined the Soweto Business Chamber’s organisation, Young Entrepreneurs of Soweto, becoming the CEO at 17.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://leadsa.co.za/articles/9231/a-special-mention-for-a-special-tree-planting-project|title=A special mention for a special tree planting project|website=leadsa.co.za}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marklives.com/2015/03/shelf-life-fatbastard-cadburyps-engen1card-schoolmedia/|title=Shelf Life: PS, there’s a new ad from Keith Rose!|date=6 March 2015|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://southerncourier.co.za/16259/youngsters-making-schools-a-better-place/|title=Young star making schools a better place - Southern Courier|date=15 November 2013|publisher=}}</ref>
==Significant events and achievements==
An initiative with his company SchoolMedia has led to over 4 500 trees being planted across [[Gauteng]], [[South Africa]] over a 4 year period.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thegreentimes.co.za/going-green_refilwe-mathebula-johnny-clegg-khethi-ngwenya-fiaz-mahomed_5/|title=Going Green_Refilwe Mathebula, Johnny Clegg, Khethi Ngwenya & Fiaz Mahomed_5 - The Green Times|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.schoolmedia.co.za/case-studies/greening-south-african-schools/|title=Greening South African schools sees 4 500 trees planted|date=17 November 2014|publisher=}}</ref> In 2012 he started another initiative with the support of [[Adidas]] and [[Orlando Pirates]], which has placed 40 new football Goalposts in 20 schools and provided school children with opportunities to meet [[Orlando Pirates]] stars like [[Benni McCarthy]] and [[Daine Klate]], or play a 5-a-side game with these professional athletes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediaupdate.co.za/publicity/51247/schoolmedia-brings-soccer-campaign-to-school-children|title=SchoolMedia brings soccer campaign to school children|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.schoolmedia.co.za/videos/orlando-pirates-football-team-visits-soweto-school/|title=Orlando Pirates visit Soweto school|date=23 February 2013|publisher=}}</ref>
==Awards== In 2013 he was one of the finalist in the Talk [[Radio 702]] Small business awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.changemakers.com/globalgoals2015/entries/khethi-ngwenyas-new-entry|title=Khethi Ngwenya&amp;#039;s New Entry|website=Changemakers}}</ref>
In 2017 he was listed the 41st most influential young [[South African]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.modernghana.com/entertainment/41099/trevor-noah-voted-2016-most-influential-young-south-african.html|title=Trevor Noah Voted 2016 Most Influential Young South African|first=Avance|last=Media|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sa.avancemedia.org/2017/01/24/trevor-noah-voted-2016-most-influential-young-south-african/|title=Most Influential Young South Africans » Trevor Noah Voted 2016 Most Influential Young South African<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=}}</ref>
==Personal life== Khethi is a [[Polyglotism|polyglot]]; he speaks several languages including [[South African English|English]], [[Zulu language|Zulu]], [[Sotho language|Sotho]], [[Tswana language|Tswana]], [[Swazi language|Swati]], [[Afrikaans]] and some [[Italian language|Italian]] and [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]. He is a [[Christian]] and a member of the [[Catholic]] church. He is of [[Swazi people|Swati]] and [[Pedi people|Pedi]] ethnicity.{{cn|date=December 2017}}
